WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.065 --> 00:00:01.245
So let's talk about something

2
00:00:01.245 --> 00:00:04.005
that's absolutely fundamental to making the digital world

3
00:00:04.005 --> 00:00:05.805
Work for everybody. Accessible

4
00:00:05.805 --> 00:00:06.805
Names. And don't worry,

5
00:00:06.805 --> 00:00:07.685
this isn't gonna get all

6
00:00:07.685 --> 00:00:08.725
technical and code heavy.

7
00:00:08.875 --> 00:00:10.525
It's really about one simple idea.

8
00:00:11.085 --> 00:00:13.885
Building a bridge, A bridge that connects every single user

9
00:00:13.905 --> 00:00:15.725
to the apps and websites we use every day.

10
00:00:16.055 --> 00:00:18.845
Let's dig in. Okay, take a look at this.

11
00:00:19.115 --> 00:00:20.165
It's a bell icon.

12
00:00:20.225 --> 00:00:21.405
You've probably clicked on a button

13
00:00:21.405 --> 00:00:22.565
just like it a thousand times.

14
00:00:23.025 --> 00:00:24.605
We look at it and we just know it means

15
00:00:24.605 --> 00:00:25.645
notifications, right?

16
00:00:26.105 --> 00:00:27.485
But what if you couldn't see it?

17
00:00:27.675 --> 00:00:29.205
What would a screen reader, the tool,

18
00:00:29.205 --> 00:00:30.285
someone who's blind uses

19
00:00:30.285 --> 00:00:32.245
to browse the web actually say out loud,

20
00:00:33.015 --> 00:00:35.505
Well, in way too many cases, this is what they hear.

21
00:00:36.205 --> 00:00:39.795
Button. That's it. Just button.

22
00:00:40.135 --> 00:00:42.035
No context, no hint of what it does.

23
00:00:42.225 --> 00:00:44.595
Imagine a page with 10 different icons

24
00:00:44.695 --> 00:00:48.195
and all you hear is button, button, button.

25
00:00:48.705 --> 00:00:50.195
It's completely unusable.

26
00:00:50.535 --> 00:00:53.675
You see a helpful bell icon, they hear a useless mystery.

27
00:00:54.365 --> 00:00:56.065
And that really gets to the heart of it.

28
00:00:56.535 --> 00:00:59.185
When we forget to give an element a proper name,

29
00:00:59.395 --> 00:01:01.785
we're not just creating some small inconvenience,

30
00:01:02.035 --> 00:01:03.425
we're creating a dead end.

31
00:01:03.635 --> 00:01:05.065
We're building a broken bridge,

32
00:01:05.285 --> 00:01:06.985
and we're leaving people stranded.

33
00:01:07.095 --> 00:01:08.905
Totally unable to use our stuff.

34
00:01:09.625 --> 00:01:12.475
Alright, so we've seen the problem, the broken bridge.

35
00:01:13.175 --> 00:01:14.875
Now let's talk about How to fix it.

36
00:01:15.295 --> 00:01:18.195
And that starts with understanding the tool for the job.

37
00:01:18.735 --> 00:01:21.235
So what exactly is an accessible name?

38
00:01:21.455 --> 00:01:24.915
Anyway, you know, the official definition from the people

39
00:01:24.915 --> 00:01:26.715
who set web standards is actually

40
00:01:26.715 --> 00:01:29.035
beautiful in its simplicity. It's just a short

41
00:01:29.035 --> 00:01:31.115
Little piece of text, that's all. But it has

42
00:01:31.295 --> 00:01:33.315
Two super critical jobs to do.

43
00:01:34.305 --> 00:01:36.725
Job number one, tell the user what it does.

44
00:01:36.865 --> 00:01:38.445
What's its purpose? A button

45
00:01:38.445 --> 00:01:41.045
that says submit tells me it's gonna send my form.

46
00:01:41.355 --> 00:01:42.925
Easy job Number two,

47
00:01:43.035 --> 00:01:46.045
distinguish it from other similar things on the page.

48
00:01:46.385 --> 00:01:48.085
If you've got two submit buttons, one

49
00:01:48.085 --> 00:01:49.725
that says submit order, and another that says,

50
00:01:49.725 --> 00:01:53.165
submit feedback tells me exactly which one I'm about to hit.

51
00:01:53.355 --> 00:01:55.725
Purpose and distinction, that's the whole game.

52
00:01:56.735 --> 00:01:59.265
Okay, so how do we actually put this into practice?

53
00:01:59.795 --> 00:02:01.745
Let's get practical with rule number one.

54
00:02:02.005 --> 00:02:05.385
And this is probably the most important of all, figuring out

55
00:02:05.385 --> 00:02:06.625
what even needs a name

56
00:02:06.625 --> 00:02:07.625
In the first place.

57
00:02:08.295 --> 00:02:10.475
For pretty much any element you see on a page

58
00:02:10.475 --> 00:02:12.875
that isn't just a block of text, you have

59
00:02:12.875 --> 00:02:14.475
to ask yourself one simple question,

60
00:02:15.055 --> 00:02:17.315
is this thing functional or is it just for

61
00:02:17.315 --> 00:02:18.315
Decoration?

62
00:02:18.545 --> 00:02:21.685
So if an element does something, if it's a button, a link,

63
00:02:21.685 --> 00:02:24.525
an image that's conveying important info, it's functional.

64
00:02:24.665 --> 00:02:25.765
And if it's functional, you

65
00:02:26.005 --> 00:02:27.045
absolutely have to give it a name.

66
00:02:27.225 --> 00:02:28.765
But if it's just there to look pretty,

67
00:02:28.915 --> 00:02:30.605
like a swirly background image

68
00:02:30.665 --> 00:02:33.205
or a simple dividing line, it's decorative.

69
00:02:33.305 --> 00:02:35.485
And in that case, you should explicitly hide it.

70
00:02:35.785 --> 00:02:36.885
And that's just as important

71
00:02:36.885 --> 00:02:38.765
because it cuts down on the digital clutter

72
00:02:38.765 --> 00:02:40.845
and lets the user focus on what actually matters.

73
00:02:41.755 --> 00:02:43.935
Now for rule number two and this one,

74
00:02:44.445 --> 00:02:45.815
This one tackles The single

75
00:02:45.845 --> 00:02:47.295
Most common mistake I see

76
00:02:47.295 --> 00:02:48.615
People make when writing these names.

77
00:02:49.495 --> 00:02:51.235
And the rule is so simple.

78
00:02:51.995 --> 00:02:54.675
Describe what the element does, not what it looks like.

79
00:02:55.065 --> 00:02:57.795
Your user needs to know its function, not its fashion.

80
00:02:58.425 --> 00:02:59.755
This is a classic example.

81
00:03:00.135 --> 00:03:03.565
You see an arrow icon, a well-meaning person might think,

82
00:03:03.875 --> 00:03:05.445
okay, I'll describe what I see.

83
00:03:05.755 --> 00:03:07.165
Blue arrow pointing, right?

84
00:03:07.745 --> 00:03:09.765
But that's totally useless information.

85
00:03:10.285 --> 00:03:12.205
A user doesn't care if it's blue or purple.

86
00:03:12.355 --> 00:03:14.205
They need to know what happens when they click it.

87
00:03:14.625 --> 00:03:17.165
And what does it do? It takes them to the next page.

88
00:03:17.665 --> 00:03:19.685
So the perfect name is just one word.

89
00:03:20.035 --> 00:03:22.085
Next function, not form.

90
00:03:22.915 --> 00:03:25.725
Okay? Our final rule is all about crafting names

91
00:03:25.755 --> 00:03:26.925
that are truly helpful.

92
00:03:27.525 --> 00:03:29.725
I want you to think of yourself as a tour guide.

93
00:03:29.785 --> 00:03:31.765
You're leading your user through your digital space,

94
00:03:31.765 --> 00:03:34.365
and you want to be as clear and efficient as possible.

95
00:03:35.465 --> 00:03:37.585
A good tour guide does three things really well.

96
00:03:37.655 --> 00:03:39.345
They're concise. They get to the point.

97
00:03:39.455 --> 00:03:41.305
They point out the most important stuff first,

98
00:03:41.645 --> 00:03:43.585
and they make sure you never get lost in a sea

99
00:03:43.585 --> 00:03:44.785
of identical looking doors.

100
00:03:45.595 --> 00:03:46.865
First, be concise.

101
00:03:47.265 --> 00:03:48.505
A screen reader is already going

102
00:03:48.505 --> 00:03:49.585
to announce the elements role.

103
00:03:49.765 --> 00:03:51.145
So if you name a button, click this

104
00:03:51.145 --> 00:03:52.345
button to submit your form.

105
00:03:52.525 --> 00:03:54.585
The user is going to hear, click this button

106
00:03:54.605 --> 00:03:56.145
to submit your form button.

107
00:03:56.535 --> 00:03:59.545
It's redundant, it's slow. Just submit is perfect.

108
00:03:59.815 --> 00:04:02.705
They'll hear a submit button, clean, fast,

109
00:04:02.805 --> 00:04:03.905
and way more effective.

110
00:04:04.405 --> 00:04:05.505
Now this brings Us to one

111
00:04:05.505 --> 00:04:08.145
of the most frustrating accessibility problems on the web.

112
00:04:08.335 --> 00:04:10.825
Imagine a screen reader user trying to quickly navigate.

113
00:04:11.055 --> 00:04:13.425
They can pull up a list of all the buttons on a page,

114
00:04:13.685 --> 00:04:14.825
and this is what they hear.

115
00:04:15.235 --> 00:04:18.945
Watch now button, watch, now, button watch, now button.

116
00:04:19.405 --> 00:04:20.905
Ugh. It's a complete dead end.

117
00:04:21.375 --> 00:04:23.665
They're just left thinking which one is which.

118
00:04:23.895 --> 00:04:24.985
They're forced to guess.

119
00:04:25.255 --> 00:04:27.625
They have to click the first one, wait for it to load,

120
00:04:27.645 --> 00:04:28.705
figure out what it is.

121
00:04:29.045 --> 00:04:32.185
Go back and try the next one. They're totally stuck.

122
00:04:32.935 --> 00:04:34.945
This is what that broken bridge feels like.

123
00:04:35.605 --> 00:04:38.065
And here's the beautiful, elegant solution.

124
00:04:38.485 --> 00:04:42.145
The visual design stays exactly the same. Clean and simple.

125
00:04:42.985 --> 00:04:44.545
Everyone just sees watch now.

126
00:04:44.845 --> 00:04:46.545
But behind the scenes in the code,

127
00:04:46.805 --> 00:04:50.105
we give each one a unique, expanded, accessible name

128
00:04:50.405 --> 00:04:52.585
so the screen reader can announce the full story.

129
00:04:52.915 --> 00:04:55.105
Watch now opening keynote watch.

130
00:04:55.205 --> 00:04:57.825
Now, inspiration, keynote, problem solved.

131
00:04:58.245 --> 00:05:00.505
Now the user knows exactly where each button goes.

132
00:05:01.315 --> 00:05:02.615
So after seeing the problem

133
00:05:02.715 --> 00:05:04.775
and walking through the rules for how to fix it,

134
00:05:04.875 --> 00:05:06.255
it really all comes down to this.

135
00:05:06.755 --> 00:05:07.935
You are the architect.

136
00:05:08.785 --> 00:05:11.615
Accessible names are the individual planks that you use

137
00:05:11.615 --> 00:05:13.815
to build that bridge between people and technology.

138
00:05:14.155 --> 00:05:16.695
And whether you're a designer, a developer, a writer,

139
00:05:16.955 --> 00:05:18.095
you're the one building it.

140
00:05:18.475 --> 00:05:20.295
You decide if that bridge is going to be sturdy

141
00:05:20.295 --> 00:05:22.255
and reliable, or if it's going to be full of holes.

142
00:05:22.955 --> 00:05:24.415
So I'll just leave you with this one question.

143
00:05:25.265 --> 00:05:27.215
Think about the websites, the apps,

144
00:05:27.435 --> 00:05:28.975
the documents that you work on.

145
00:05:29.795 --> 00:05:32.575
What's one broken bridge, one missing name,

146
00:05:32.955 --> 00:05:35.415
one unhelpful icon that you can go back

147
00:05:35.415 --> 00:05:37.215
and fix right now today.
